N2  - Background: Psychotic disorders are linked to cognitive deficits. Foremost among these is impaired information processing speed. Neuroimaging in healthy participants links processing speed to fronto-parietal control network (FPCN) activity. Notably, this finding implicates both the cortical and cerebellar nodes of the FPCN. Cerebellar-cortical hypoconnectivity is a well replicated neuroimaging phenotype in psychotic disorders. We hypothesized that cerebellar-cortical hypoconnectivity is a direct cause of impaired information processing speed. We tested this hypothesis in a two-part experiment. Methods: Circuit identification: A cohort participants with bipolar disorder with psychosis (n=21) underwent a rsfMRI scan and MATRICS testing. Functional connectivity between a midline cerebellar FPCN ROI and whole brain was regressed against BACS symbol coding score. Circuit validation: In participants with schizophrenia (n=12), we conducted a sham controlled trial of transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) to midline cerebellum. Stimulation was delivered twice a day for 5 days. rsfMRI connectivity and BACS symbol coding score were assessed at baseline and 1 week following the last TMS session. Within-subject change in cerebellar connectivity was regressed against change in BACS score. Results: In the circuit identification study, connectivity between midline cerebellar FPCN and cortical FPCN correlated with symbol processing speed (p<.05). In the TMS-fMRI study, restoration of cerebellar-cortical FPCN connectivity was correlated with improved BACS score (p<.05). Conclusions: Hypoconnectivity in a cerebellar-cortical network correlates with transdiagnostic information processing deficits in psychotic disorders. Manipulation of this network demonstrates a causal link between circuit connectivity and cognition as well as identifying a therapeutic target for medication refractory deficits. Supported By: Sydney Baer Foundation, NIMH grants K23 MH100623, R01 MH111868, K23 MH091210 Keywords: Information Processing, Psychotic Bipolar Disorder, Schizophrenia, TMS, Resting state fMRI
