N2  - Background: Schizophrenia is present in ∼1% of the population, producing severe consequences in overall functioning. Rates of cannabis use disorder (CUD) are high in this population, with ∼1 in every 4 individuals concurrently presenting with a diagnosis of CUD versus ∼3% in the general population. CUD in schizophrenia is associated with worsened symptomatology, and cognitive impairment. Individuals with schizophrenia are known to exhibit difficulties in quitting cannabis and remaining abstinent, which may relate to prefrontal cortical dysfunction. The goal of this study is to identify correlative biomarkers related to cannabis abstinence and brain stimulation (repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation, rTMS) treatment outcome in schizophrenia co-morbid with CUD. Methods: A statistical model will be curated using demographics, clinical symptoms, and neuropsychological/neurophysiological measures. Participants are administered active or sham rTMS 5x/week for 4 weeks (blinded), before and after which a battery of cognitive/neurophysiological tasks will be conducted, and cannabis use will be monitored through self-report and quantitative urine toxicology. Results: To date, 15 individuals with schizophrenia or schizoaffective disorder have been recruited (mean 31.89 years). These individuals used 1.16 grams/day of cannabis and used cannabis daily for 8.6 years. Based on self-report/urine toxicology, one individual remained abstinent through the trial, while 13 did not use for at least one week. Moreover, data on cognition/neurophysiology of the participants has been collected and will be analyzed by correlative statistics. Conclusions: This study increase our understanding of biomarkers associated with quitting or reducing cannabis use in people with schizophrenia. Supported By: NIDA; CIHR Keywords: Cannabis Use Disorder, Schizophrenia, rTMS, Neurophysiology, Neuropsychology
