N2  - Alzheimer’s disease (AD) is a neurodegenerative disorder that induces severe disruption of large-scale brain networks connectivity. Repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS), as an effective tool to modulate connectivity, may represent a potential treatment for AD by boosting connectivity of the impaired systems. Considering the highly inter-individual variability in the anatomical localization of networks’ hubs together with the functional alterations associated with the progressive nature of AD, individually targeting the stimulation site may represent the turning point into the effectiveness of rTMS intervention. This approach has been reported to significantly increase the efficacy of rTMS treatments in depression but has never been adopted in AD interventions, which have been relying solely on average coordinates. AD pathophysiology has been mainly associated with a breakdown of the Default Mode Network (DMN), which plays a crucial role in episodic memory retrieval, and of Central Executive Network (CEN), supporting executive functions. We present an ongoing study with an innovative tailored network-based rTMS treatment, which aims at ameliorating cognitive symptoms in AD. This novel protocol consists in targeting DMN and CEN hubs identified from the individual MRI scans. We hypothesize that the rTMS treatment will enhance connectivity of the stimulated network, producing an improvement that reflects the specific cognitive functions supported by the stimulated network: more pronounced episodic memory improvement after DMN stimulation, enhanced executive functions after CEN stimulation. After recruitment, patients are randomly assigned to one of three rTMS treatments: DMN, CEN or placebo. A high frequency rTMS protocol (20 Hz at 100% of the resting motor threshold) is applied during an intensive phase (3 weeks, 5 days per week) followed by a maintenance phase (bimonthly sessions for 5 months). DMN is stimulated targeting the left inferior parietal lobe, whereas CEN by stimulating left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex. Target coordinates are extracted from resting-state fMRI individual data. At baseline (t0), at the end of the intensive phase (t1) and of the maintenance phase (t2) patients are administered with ADAS-Cog scale and with Paired Associative Learning and Spatial Working Memory subtest of CANTAB battery. In addition, neural mechanisms underlying the clinical response are evaluated with an integrated multi-modal imaging approach: MRI acquisitions and TMS-EEG co-registrations are conducted at t0, t1 and t2. Preliminary data (N = 6) supports the feasibility of this innovative study and allow to outline the key points to consider when planning personalized network-based rTMS treatment for AD patients, paving the way toward the development of effective interventions able to slow down the progression of the disease.
