N2  - Question: Even with effective antiretroviral treatment, individuals with HIV infection continue to develop HIV-associated neurocognitive disorders (HAND). As these individuals age, they may also experience age-related changes in cognitive function, and substantial research suggests that HIV infection may accelerate the process of cognitive aging. Since cognitive function is related to a variety of functional behaviors such as self-care, medication adherence and driving, interventions for maintaining and improving cognition in this group are important. Previously, we reported a pilot study of tDCS and cognitive training that had shown promising preliminary results. We have subsequently begun a more definitive trial with the same training protocol with the key hypotheses that tDCS combined with cognitive training would produce greater improvements in working memory, attention, and verbal memory than training alone. The purpose of this study was to investigate the impact of cognitive training with or without transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) on cognition in older adults with HIV infection. Methods: Participants completed preliminary self-report of cognitive difficulties and neuropsychological assessments to establish a diagnosis of HIV-related Mild Neurocognitive Disorder (MND) using the Frascati criteria. After baseline assessments individuals completed six 20-min training sessions. The active and sham groups completed the same cognitive training protocol, but the active group received active tDCS consisting of anodal stimulation to left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (F3) with cathode at the right frontal pole (Fp2) while the other two groups received sham stimulation. After completing the training protocol, participants again completed the assessment battery. Results: The final sample included 48 individuals aged 50 years and older (38 men and 10 women; 35 blacks and 13 white; mean age 57.8 years; mean years of education 12.6). In the model for working memory, the effect of time (repeated assessments) approach statistical significance (p = 0.08), but the interaction of treatment group by time was not significant (p = 0.26). Examination of the plot of means suggested the presence of substantial training effects compared to results in the control group. This result was associated with a moderate effect size ([Formula presented] = 0.066; d = 0.53). Other outcome measures showed similar effect sizes. Conclusions: These results confirm our previous findings and suggest that cognitive training with and without tDCS may have a positive effect on working memory in older persons with HAND. Although group differences were not significantly significant, across outcomes they suggested a benefit and were consistent with a moderate effect size. Further exploration should investigate the extent to which cognitive training with or without stimulation can have an impact on functional behaviors (see Fig. 1). Funded by the US National Institute on Aging (R21 AG056256).
