N2  - Question: Alzheimer’s disease (AD) is a life-consuming disease affecting brain functions and the quality of life. Till now, no pharmacological treatments were found to be effective. Recently, transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS)- or working memory training (WMT)-induced cognitive benefits are well established in preclinical AD, tDCS-enhanced effect on WMT-induced cognitive benefits are less understood. Methods: In a double-blinded, sham-controlled clinical trial, we investigated the enhancing effect of tDCS on learning and memory function, tDCS-enhanced effects on WMT-induced effect on learning and memory function in 201 senior adults with mild neurocognitive disorder due to Alzheimer’s disease (NCD-AD). Word-list learning test, including three learning trials and one trial of delayed recall, was used to assess the learning and memory function. The raw number of word recalled on trial 3 refers to best learning. Learn over trials (LOT) is computed by taking the sum of correctly recalled across the trial 1 to trial 3 corrected for mean word span, representing the ability to improve upon trial 1 performance during each of the subsequent two learning trials. Results: Both WMT and tDCS has positive effect on memory and learning function at 4th week. But combined tDCS and WMT showed highest scores of both best learning (p = 0.008) and LOT (p = 0.002). Conclusions: TDCS and WMT shows positive effect on brain function generally; meanwhile, tDCS can particularly enhance the efficacy of working memory training on learning function.
