N2  - Question: Intermittent theta-burst stimulation (iTBS) applied over the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) has been shown to relieve symptoms of major depression disorder (MDD). However, there are few published studies probing the curative potential of stimulation targets outside the prefrontal cortex. While, traditionally, the selection of stimulation targets has been constrained to anatomical target regions near the surface of the brain, new approaches utilize patients” individual functional MRI data in order to identify superficial cortical stimulation targets that are functionally connected to deeper regions of the brain, thus enabling propagation of iTBS effects. The present study investigates the effects of stimulation of parietal-hippocampal functional connectivity on the hippocampus (HC) and depressive symptoms as well as cognition in patients with MDD. Methods: 53 patients with unipolar MDD were randomized to three treatment groups and underwent 15 days of iTBS. All patients received one daily session of active iTBS over DLPFC as well as a second daily session of (1) active iTBS over DLPFC (DLPFC-DLPFC group, n = 17), (2) active iTBS over individualized targets within lateral parietal cortex (LPC) based on functional connectivity to the HC (DLPFC-LPC group, n = 18), or (3) sham iTBS either over DLPFC or LPC (DLPFC-SHAM group, n = 18). Depressive symptom severity was assessed over the treatment course using the Hamilton Depression Rating Scale (HDRS-17). Before and after the treatment course patients underwent MRI scanning to acquire functional data at rest and during the performance of an associative memory paradigm. Results: HDRS-17 scores improved across treatment groups, however, in the absence of significant between-group differences. In the associative memory fMRI task patients in the DLPFC-DLPFC group showed greater activation in the left HC during encoding at the end of treatment than patients in the DLPFC-LPC and DLPFC-SHAM groups when controlling for pre-treatment scores. Only in the DLPFC-LPC group, this increase in neural activation was correlated with better outcome in a spatial planning task post-treatment. Functional connectivity analysis revealed a significant effect of group on functional connectivity changes between right HC and a cluster in the left DLPFC. Conclusion: These findings provide evidence for the propagating effects of iTBS over an individualized parietal target on hippocampal plasticity: firstly, parietal-hippocampal stimulation enhanced encoding-related activity in the HC. Secondly, stimulation of both DLPFC and the parietal target augmented functional connectivity between DLPFC and HC. Thus, while parietal-hippocampal stimulation had no additional clinical benefit regarding depressive symptom severity, the correlation between increased neural activation and better performance during spatial planning suggests that the tested approach may be beneficial for depressed patients with cognitive deficits.
