N2  - Introduction: Prefrontal cortex oscillations on the theta frequency band (4–7 Hz) have been associated with several cognitive processes. Moreover, prefrontal neural activities were found to be phase-locked with subcortical structures in the theta band, including thalamus and hippocampus, which suggests a role of this oscillation in the interactions between these structures. In animal models, theta band phase-locked stimulation of the hippocampus led to significantly different plasticity profiles according to the phase of that oscillation. Objectives: In the present study we aim to translate these investigations to human subjects in a non-invasive fashion, using repetitive stimulation of the prefrontal cortex during different phases of the local theta oscillation. Materials & methods: 16 healthy volunteers participated in the study. We applied 400 EEG-triggered 100 Hz-triple pulses (1200 stimuli in total) with an inter-trigger interval of 3 ± 1 s at 120% resting-motor threshold (RMT), targeting the left dorsomedial prefrontal cortex (lDMPFC) with neuronavigation, in three trigger conditions on different days: (1) at the theta oscillation positive peak, (2) negative peak, (3) random phase. Prefrontal theta was estimated using 126-channel EEG and a source-based spatial filter sensitive to dipoles at the lDMPFC, individually segmented cortical meshes were employed with oscillating dipoles having outward facing orientation, and an online phase-detection algorithm. We investigated the changes of evoked cortical responses before and after each intervention using TMS-EEG to the lDMPFC (160 pulses real TMS at 120% RMT followed by 160 pulses sham coil TMS). Outcome variables were TMS evoked potentials and induced oscillations. Results: The negative theta-peak plasticity protocol significantly increased the power of the induced theta oscillation within the ipsilateral prefrontal cortex, and an opposite result was derived from the positive theta-peak protocol (i.e. decreased power of induced theta oscillation). No significant change was observed from the random phase stimulation. TMS evoked potentials remained unaffected by either one of the interventions. Conclusion: These results suggest that TMS plasticity protocols phase-locked to the prefrontal theta oscillation lead to different profiles of cortical response depending on the phase of the stimulation. It is possible that by delivering stimuli at the theta negative peak we strengthened the circuits responsible for this oscillatory activity and weakened it by positive peak stimulation. This has potential implications for clinical use, as protocols with more reliable induction of neuroplasticity might show better effect sizes in treatment for neuropsychiatric diseases. Specifically, successful modulation of the prefrontal theta oscillation might have therapeutic effects in disorders associated with learning and cognitive deficits.
