N2  - Introduction: It is well known that cognition begins to decline with age, but these functions are also compromised in various neurological and psychiatric disorders. Cortical regions such as the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (dlPFC) and its associated networks exhibit dysfunctional activity in a multitude of mental illnesses. Neuromodulation of cortical areas via noninvasive brain stimulation (NIBS) modalities is emerging as a promising treatment option to optimize regional and network activity in order to reverse cognitive impairment. Therefore, we surveyed the literature for high quality evidence. Methods: The databases Ovid, Medline, and Embase were searched using the terms: (((((transcranial magnetic stimulation) OR transcranial direct current stimulation)) AND ((traumatic brain injuries) AND mood disorders))) OR ((((transcranial magnetic stimulation) OR transcranial direct current stimulation)) AND ((dementia) AND ((cognition disorders) OR cognit∗ impairment))). The filters “english language” and “humans” were applied to the initial search. We adhered to PRISMA guidelines and the results were manually sorted into randomized controlled studies by three independent reviewers. Results: 360 initial results were filtered to distill 43 randomized/sham controlled trials. Of these, 31 (72%) demonstrated statistical significance superior to sham. Positive effects of NIBS (rTMS, tDCS, tRNS) were found in a wide distribution of conditions: ADHD (0/1), Alzheimer's disease/MCI (8/9), Depression (5/8), Fibromyalgia (1/2), Healthy Controls (2/2), HIV (1/1), Huntington's disease (1/1), Multiple Sclerosis (1/2), Parkinson's disease (2/4), Schizophrenia (6/9), and Stroke (3/3). These studies assessed multiple variables and improvements in cognition were observed across all six neurocognitive domains: Complex Attention (12/18), Executive Function (17/25), Learning and Memory (11/14), Perceptual-Motor Function (8/10), and Social Cognition (3/3). Positive results stratified according to stimulation modality are as follows: repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) = 13/22; transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) = 15/17; transcranial random noise stimulation (tRNS) = 1/2; rTMS + tDCS = 1/1; tDCS + pharmacotherapy = 1/1. The left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex was overwhelmingly the most common anatomical target; though other regions were stimulated as well. Conclusion: These results demonstrate improvements in cognition across a variety of neuropsychiatric disorders spanning the spectrum of neurocognitive domains. The findings are especially significant in the context of expected increase in prevalence of dementia concomitant with the rising proportion of seniors (65+). In addition to serving as an adjunct to neuropsychiatric disorders, NIBS offers a favorable side effect profile to circumvent polypharmacy that plagues the increasingly aging population. (Figure Presented).
