N2  - Background: Transcranial alternating current stimulation (tACS) has been found to modulate a wide range of cognitive functions. Frontal-midline theta oscillations are strongly related to conflict processing [1,2], and accordingly, theta-range tACS has been found to reduce stimulus-response (S-R) interference (i.e. Simon conflict) [3,4]. In addition, it has not yet been examined whether a similar beneficial effect is evident on other types of interference such as conflict between stimuli (S-S; i.e. Stroop-like interference). Objective: The aim of the present study was to compare the effects of online and offline theta-range tACS to a sham condition on both S-S and S-R types of interference. Methods: In this single-blind, randomized, sham-controlled study, twenty-two healthy young adults were assigned into active or sham group. A 0° phase, 6 Hz stimulation was administered with a length of 20 minutes for the experimental group and 30 s for the sham group. To measure conflict processing, a reaction time (RT) task [5] was used including the following four conditions: (1) no interference; (2) S-R interference introduced by incongruency between the location of the target stimulus and the corresponding response hand; (3) S-S interference introduced by incongruency between the color of the target stimulus and the flanking stimulus; (4) double conflict containing both S-R and S-S types of interference. Accuracy, median RT and linear integrated speed-accuracy scores were calculated. Performance was recorded during the stimulation (online), and approximately 20 minutes after the end of the stimulation (offline). A mixed ANOVA was performed with session (online, offline) and conflict (no interference, S-S, S-R, double interference) as within-subject factors and the type of stimulation (active, sham) as grouping variable. Post hoc tests with Bonferroni correction were performed for the comparison between groups. Results: Participants in the active group showed longer RTs compared to the sham group (F(3, 60) = 2.405, p = 0.048, η2 = 0.107) in each condition, except for the S-R condition which showed a non-significant tendency (p = 0.073). RTs did not differ from the sham group during the offline stimulation. TACS did not affect the accuracy (F(3, 60) = 2.463, p = 0.71, η2 = 0.110) or the linear integrated speed-accuracy score (F(3, 60) = 1.359, p = 0.264, η2 = 0.064). Discussion: Results suggest that tACS with the specific protocol in this study might only affect the speed of conflict processing without modulating the accuracy or behavioral efficiency. Online stimulation does not seem to improve S-R interference but promotes conflict monitoring or hinders performance on other forms of interference processing. These findings implicate that tACS might modulate different types of interference separately. Moreover, the current results raise the possibility that different montages affect cognitive control functions differently. Disclosure statement: ‘Acknowledgment: This study was supported by the grants EFOP 3.6.3-VEKOP-16-2017-00009 and the UNKP-19-3 New National Excellence Program of the Ministry of Human Capacities’.
