N2  - Our previous studies indicated that chronic mild stress procedure (CMS) induced cognitive dysfunction observed using Novell Object Recognition (NOR). This impairment was observed in Wistar HAN rats as well as in a genetic model of depression, the Wistar Kyoto strain and was reversed by deep brain stimulation (DBS) with electrodes in the vmPFC (ventral medial prefrontal cortex) area. Therefore, we have attempted to identify molecular markers of these effects using the TaqMan Low Density Array (TLDA). mRNA from PFC was reverse transcribed with random hexamers to generate single-stranded cDNA transcripts according to the manufacturer's protocol of the High Capacity cDNA Archive Kit (Applied Biosystems). For qPCR reactions, cDNA from five individuals was taken for each group. A predesigned TaqMan Low Density Array (TLDA) in a 24 format (Applied Biosystems) was used, and duplicates were performed for the expression of each gene in each sample. Based on the literature survey genes of interest that are believed to be crucial in depression and stress were selected for our study (e.g. Gdi1 - Rab GDP dissociation inhibitor alpha or ID-1- NA-binding protein inhibitor ID-1 or 5HT7A -5-hydroxytryptamine receptor 7). We didn’t observe statistically significant correlations between gene expression and above mentioned cognitive deficit, however we noticed similar pattern in NOR results and 5HT7A receptor mRNA expression in Wistar HAN PFC. Interestingly difference between both strains were observed in mRNA expression of GDi1. Moreover, the interaction between stress and DBS was observed at the level of several genes. Detail data will be discussed. Although we didn’t observe any biochemical markers of cognitive dysfunction, we have found significant differences in the expression of genes differentiating two rat strains. Supported by grant NCN Opus 9, no: 2015/17/B/NZ7/02979
