N2  - Post stroke impairment includes sensory, motor and cognitive impairments impose a stressful situation and a great burden to the patients, their families, and the society. The tDCS along with Fluoxetine & Dual Task Training is a promising technique to treat a wide range of neurological conditions including stroke. The result of current study may help in the development of new neurorehabilitation tool to improve lower limb motor recovery of stroke patients. Aims & objectives: To determine the efficacy of combination therapy with drug, device, and exercise (Fluoxetine, tDCS, & DTT) for improving post stroke gait. Materials & methods: N = 224. Single-centre, double blinded randomized controlled trial. Randomly allocated into 1 of 4 different treatment groups using a process of computer generated blinded random number & opaque and sealed envelopes. Study arm: Group-A: tDCS + Fluoxetine + DTT; Group- B: Sham tDCS + Fluoxetine + DTT; Group- C: tDCS + placebo drug + DTT; Group- D: Sham tDCS + placebo drug + DTT 12 sessions of bihemispheric active/sham tDCS (2 mA) with each session lasting for 20 min followed by 2 extra sessions every other week. 20 mg of Fluoxetine/placebo drug is given by mouth daily for 6 weeks. DTT started within 1 hour after each bihemispheric tDCS session and last for 45 min. Outcome measures: at baseline, at 6 weeks and at 12 weeks; Primary outcomes: 1. Gait analysis variables, 2. FMA-LE; Secondary outcomes: 1. NIHSS, 2. mRS, 3. MAS, 4. BBS, 5. TUG, 6. FRT, 7. mBI Result: 600 subjects assessed for eligibility. 435 subjects excluded not meeting inclusion criteria. We included 165 subjects and randomly allocated into one of four groups. 45 subjects allocated to Group-A, 39 subjects allocated to Group-B, 45subjects allocated to Group-C, and 36 subjects allocated to Group-D. Conclusion: Study is ongoing RCT, so conclusion is awaited.
