N2  - Introduction: Alzheimer's disease (AD) is a chronic and irreversible neurodegenerative disease featuring deficits in cognitive performance, with memory impairment typically reported as the initial presenting complaint. Common treatments can not prevent or reverse the course of the illness, and new efforts in the development of therapy are critically needed. Recently, repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS), a non-invasive brain stimulation tool, has been proposed as a promising approach to improve the clinical manifestation of AD. In this study, we aimed to investigate the benefit of personalized rTMS targeting based on individual resting state functional magnetic resonance imaging (RS-fMRI). Methods: A single-blind (subject), randomized, sham-controlled trial was conducted in twenty subjects with a diagnosis of AD. Subjects were randomized to rTMS or sham control for 2 weeks (one session daily, 5 days a week). The stimulation site was an individualized left lateral parietal location that showed high functional connectivity with the left hippocampal seed based on personal RS-fMRI data before the study. Mini Mental State Examination (MMSE), Clinical Dementia Rating Scale (CDR) and 12-word Philadelphia Verbal Learning Test (PVLT) were assessed prior to and immediately after the intervention. Results: Both groups did not improve significantly their performance in MMSE and CDR after the treatment. However, there was significantly greater improvement in PVLT List A Total Learning and Long Delay Recall with rTMS compared to the sham intervention. Conclusion: Individualized rTMS treatment over the left parietal cortex has a beneficial effect in episodic memory, and may represent a promising treatment for memory dysfunction in Alzheimer patients. Acknowledgements: Jintao Wang and Lili Wei contributed equally to this project. The project was supported by the NSFC Projects of International Cooperation and Exchanges (No: 8161101010), National Key Research & Development Program of China (No: 2017YFC1310502) to W. Chen.
