N2  - Introduction: Advances in Spinal Cord Stimulation (SCS) have improved patient outcomes and overall adoption of SCS for the treatment of chronic pain. In addition, continuous technological developments allow for opportunities to address previously un-met patient needs. Given the highly dynamic nature of chronic pain, an SCS device that can provide multiple neurostimulation options is thought likely to be a valuable tool for addressing the specific needs of patients. Recent data suggests that chronic pain patients, when given a choice, often will utilize a variety of SCS waveforms (Berg A., et al., 2017; Metzger C. et al., 2018), thereby suggesting that personalized application of neurostimulation may be a more desired and/or effective approach for managing chronic pain. Here, we present initial results from prospectively-collected clinical data using a system that allows for personalized SCS-based treatment for chronic pain via patient utilization of combination therapy (simultaneous or sequential) and/or waveform automation. Methods: VERITAS is a prospective, multicenter, open-label study designed to investigate the value of an SCS system capable of multiple modalities in obtaining clinically significant pain relief in chronic pain patients (Precision Spectra WaveWriter, Boston Scientific). Subjects with a positive trial will receive a permanent implant and are followed up per study schedule up to 2 years. Assessments collected will include NRS, quality of life, ODI, and other endpoints. Key inclusion criteria include eligible candidates for SCS with no back surgery in the 6 months prior to screening. Subjects with significant cognitive impairment that may confound study results are excluded. Results: This report will provide details of the study design, preliminary outcomes including change in NRS scores compared to baseline, programming related information and patient usage of multiple waveforms and field shapes etc. Conclusion: This study aims to share experience regarding the use of newly introduced SCS system that can provide multiple neurostimulation modalities. This is particularly relevant in patients who prefer multiple available options to manage their chronic pain.
