N2  - Currently, no effective intervention exists for people at increased risk for dementia. While recent reviews have highlighted promising results for cognitive training (CT), randomized controlled trials (RCTs) in people diagnosed with mild cognitive impairment (MCI) have shown modest efficacy for memory improvement. Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is a safe, non-invasive technique, which can enhance cognitive functioning. This double-blind, sham-controlled, parallel group RCT examined whether tDCS + CT is more effective than CT alone for improving memory. 68 participants diagnosed with amnestic MCI (aMCI) were randomized to receive either Active tDCS (2mA for 30 min and 0.016mA for 30 min) or Sham tDCS (0.016mA for 60 min) combined with computerized CT for 15 sessions given over a period of 5 to 6 weeks. The primary outcome measure was the California Verbal Learning Task 2nd Edition (CVLT-II), a non-trained test of verbal learning and memory. Intention-to-treat (ITT) analysis showed that the Active tDCS + CT group significantly improved at post treatment (p =.033), and the Sham tDCS + CT group did not (p =.050), but there was no difference between groups. At the 3 month follow-up, both groups showed large sized memory effects compared to baseline, with Active tDCS + CT group improving 1.13 SD and the Sham tDCS + CT group 0.84 SD, although there was no significant difference between groups. At 3 month follow-up both groups showed significant functional improvements (ps <.01). Active tDCS + CT did not cause greater memory improvement compared to Sham tDCS + CT. Both conditions resulted in larger-sized and more sustained memory improvements than prior trials of CT in participants with aMCI. These outcomes raise the possibility that both active and sham tDCS may have enhanced the effects of CT, and that “sham tDCS” at 0.016 mA may have biological effects. Keywords: transcranial direct current stimulation, cognitive training, mild cognitive impairment
