N2  - Introduction: The standing postural control is dependent upon numerous inputs interacting across multiple temporal-spatial scales. As such, the dynamics of its output, i.e., postural sway, is physiologically complex. Studies have shown the degree of postural sway complexity is often diminished by aging and diseases. Spinocerebellar ataxia (SCA) is a neurodegenerative disorder caused by dysfunction of the cerebellum and its connected neural networks. People with SCA often had impaired standing postural control, and recent studies using repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) can improve the postural control performance in SCA. We thus hypothesize that rTMS may increase the postural sway complexity in SCA. Methods: Twenty participants aged 18-75 years with SCA confirmed by genetic testing, and 20 age- and sex-matched healthy participants completed this study. Both cohorts completed baseline tests, consisting of two, 30-second standing trials on the force plate under eyes-open and eyes-closed condition in randomized order. The SCA cohort was then separated into two groups and each group received 20 sessions of real or sham rTMS targeting the cerebellum over four weeks respectively. Then the SCA cohort completed the same standing test protocol within three days, and after two weeks following the last rTMS session. The multiscale entropy was used to quantify the postural sway complexity in both anterior-posterior (AP) and medio-lateral (ML) directions. Results: At baseline, SCA cohort had significantly lower postural sway complexity in both eyes-open and eyes-closed conditions compared to the healthy cohort (p<0.001). As compared to sham, participants had significant increases in postural sway complexity in both eyes-open and eyes-closed conditions following real rTMS (p<0.05), and such increase in eye-closed condition can sustain for at least two weeks (p=0.04). These results demonstrate that the SCA diminishes the physiologic complexity of standing postural control, and rTMS may be an effective strategy to restore such loss of complexity. Keywords: rTMS, spinocerebellar ataxia, standing postural control, complexity
