N2  - Background: Effects on non-motor symptoms, for example cognitive side effects, could influence the decision for either globus pallidus pars interna (GPi) or subthalamic nucleus (STN) deep brain stimulation (DBS) in Parkinson's disease (PD). Additionally, studies investigating preoperative cognition in relation to functional health (FH) and quality of life (QoL) after surgery have reported contrasting results. Objectives: 1) comparing GPi and STN DBS on cognitive outcomes three years after surgery and 2) investigating the relation between preoperative cognitive status, FH and QoL three years after surgery. Methods: Patients were randomized to receive GPi (n=65) or STN DBS (n=63). Standardized assessments were performed at baseline, one year, and three years. We used linear mixed model analyses to investigate between-group differences on various neuropsychological tests three years after DBS. Preoperative cognitive status was assessed using modified MDS PD-MCI criteria at baseline (PDmci: mild cognitive impairment, vs PDnc: normal cognition). The AMC Linear Disability Score and the PD quality of life questionnaire were used to assess FH and QoL. Linear mixed model analyses were performed to compare cognitive groups on 3-year outcome. Results: Eighty-seven patients (68%) completed at least one neuropsychological test after three years. There were no significant differences on cognitive functioning between GPi and STN DBS three years after surgery (p-values between 0.17 and 0.87). There were no differences between pre-operative PDmci (n=23) and PDnc (n=66) on FH and QoL three years after surgery (p-values between 0.41 and 0.77). Conclusions: These results suggest that pre-operative (mild) cognitive impairments do not provide a clear direction for clinicians when considering STN or GPi as a target for DBS. Keywords: Parkinson's disease, DBS, cognition, mild cognitive impairment.
