N2  - Background:Associative memory deficits are common in neurodegenerative disease and novel therapies aimed at improving these faculties are needed. Non-invasive, focal, and mechanism based stimulation strategies may be ideal. Objective:To assess the effect of high-definition transcranial alternating current stimulation (HD-TACS) on associative memory (AM) performance in young adults. We hypothesized that focal delivery of theta HD-TACS to the right fusiform cortex would result in improved visual AM performance compared to sham and anodal direct current stimulation. Methods:Participants were randomized into one of three groups: HD-TACS (6 Hz), HD-TDCS, or sham stimulation. Subjects performed a visual AM task at baseline, followed by a second performance where stimulation was applied during encoding. Memory was tested immediately and after a 24-hour delay. Factorial ANOVA assessed the influence of group, baseline performance, and gender on memory scores. Age, education, and side-effect profile were also compared between groups. Results:There was no significant difference between groups in age, education, or baseline performance on the associative memory task. Immediately after stimulation, subjects receiving HD-TACS had higher correct memory scores than the HD-TDCS or sham groups. The HD-TACS group also had lower false memory then the HD-TDCS group. Group differences were no longer significant at 24 hours, though a trend was observed. Conclusion:HD-TACS, delivered to the right fusiform cortex at 6 Hz, improved visual AM performance in healthy subjects. This work provides evidence for a causal role of visual association cortex in associative memory encoding and suggests a novel strategy for treating cognitive impairment. Keywords: TACS, cognition, fusiform cortex, HD-TES
