N2  - Introduction: Post-Stroke Depression (PSD) reaches nearly a third of stroke survivors, early or late, affecting their functional recovery and quality of life. Repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS) has been explored as a safe supporting tool in the treatment of PSD. Objective: Evaluate the effects of rTMS on PSD and quality of life of post-stroke patients. Methods: This is a prospective clinical study, self-control case (SCC). Convenience sample (n=15) separated in two groups (excitatory stimulation, n=8; inhibitory stimulation, n=7) underwent 20 sessions of rTMS. Individuals were assessed with Hamilton Scale (HAM-D) for depression and WHOQOL-BREF questionnaire for quality of life. Results: Both groups presented a significant change in the score of all WHOQOL-BREF domains and in HAM-D. Conclusion: The findings of this clinical study suggest that rTMS can be a promising tool, capable to relieve depressive symptoms and helpful in the improvement of post-stroke patients's quality of life. 2 Introduction: According to the American Heart Association, every 3 minutes and 45 seconds, stroke kills someone in the US[1]. Globally it is the second leading cause of death and one of the main causes of disability[2]. Post-stroke depression (PSD) is a serious psychiatric complication often reported after stroke, and nearly one-third of stroke survivors suffer from its symptoms, early or late, what affect their functional recovery and quality of life[3]. Antidepressants, especially Selective Serotonin Reuptake Inhibitors (SSRIs), are indicated as a good choice for therapeutic intervention, although their benefits are not expressive in preventing PSD or perhaps improving neurological outcomes[4]. In addition, it has been reported that the use of Tricyclic Antidepressants (TCAs), SSRIs or various types may increase the risk of recurrence of stroke in some patients[5]. In recent years, repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS) has been explored as a safe supporting tool in the treatment of PSD by many researchers. However, further studies are needed on this topic to test the consistency of the results[6]. 3 Methods: This is a prospective clinical study, self-control case (SCC), performed at the Neuromodulation Laboratory of Dr. Henrique Santillo State Rehabilitation Center (CRER), Goiás, Brazil, from June/2016 until May/2017. Among the patients registered on the waiting list for outpatient treatment of CRER, we selected those with: (a) a history of stroke either in the right and/or left hemispheres; (b) for at least six months; (c) confirmed by nuclear magnetic resonance; (d) aged between 21 and 80 years; (e) with symptoms of depression and (f) with absence of severe cognitive dysfunction or aphasia. We excluded from this study, patients who: (a) were already on outpatient therapy at any other department of CRER; (b) had other psychiatric or neurological diseases associated with stroke; (c) had a history of epilepsy; (d) had the presence of metal in the skull or cardiac pacemaker; and (e) used antidepressant medication or had a history of depression before stroke. The rTMS intervention was discontinued for patients who: (f) presented non-tolerance to the stimulation side effects; (g) had less than 75% of frequency in the sessions of the treatment program. The primary outcomes were: (a) PSD, assessed with Hamilton Scale for Depression (HAM-D), which evaluates the intensity of depressive symptoms - the higher the score, the greater the level of depression; and (b) Quality of Life, assessed by the WHOQOL-BREF questionnaire, which score ranges from zero to 100 - the higher the score, the better the quality of life. Convenience sample (n=15) underwent 20 sessions of rTMS, 20 minutes per day, 5 days per week (monday – friday). The motor threshold was done following the 10/20 international system and the stimulation targets were: (a) active stimulation of 10 Hz on Dorso Lateral Prefrontal Cortex (DLPFC), F3 (n=8), using 80 to 90% of motor threshold with interval of 25 seconds, stimuli/5 seconds and trains of 50 pulses, when the lesion was in the Right Hemisphere or in other regions that were not left DLPFC; and (b) inhibition stimulation of 1Hz on right DLPFC, F4 (n=7), using 80 to 90% of motor threshold with zero interval, being one pulse per second, when the lesion was on the left DLPFC or in regions close to that target. The high-speed magnetic neurostimulator used was the Neurosoft Company (Neuro/MS, Russia). The assessment using HAM-D e WHOQOL-BREF was done in 3 different moments: before starting the protocol (A1), on its closure (A2) and one month after its end (A3). The scores of the questionnaires were compared based on the Friedman test, followed by the Wilcoxon test. The level of significance was 5%. 4 Results: All patients concluded the treatment. Both groups presented a significant change in the score of all WHOQOL-BREF domains and in HAM-D. In the group that received intervention with the inhibition protocol (F4), score changes were continuous and gradual, comparing A1, A2 and A3. In the (F3) stimulated group, though, the improvement of scores appeared later, being more significant between A1 and A3. [Figure presented] [Figure presented] 5 Discussion and Conclusion: In this study, we evaluated the effect of rTMS in the treatment of PSD, using active stimulation protocols in left DLPFC (F3) and inhibition in right DLPFC (F4). Although the mechanisms of action of rTMS on PSD remain uncertain, studies have shown its efficacy in the remission of depressive symptoms in this kind of patients[6]. They also suggest that rTMS can regulate mood through the inhibitory low frequency (1 Hz) stimulation and excitatory high frequency (5-20 Hz) stimulation [3] [7]. Several authors have researched inhibitory and excitatory protocols and reported not only as effective choices for the treatment of depression [8], [9], but also in the treatment of aphasias and motor sequels, etc. [10]. These protocols are based on the assumption that the greatest challenge in the brain recovery of post-stroke patients is not the injury itself, but the hyperactivity in the healthy hemisphere contralateral to the injury, which causes an inter hemispheric imbalance. In order to recover this balance, when low frequency rTMS (≤ 1 Hz) is applied on the healthy hemisphere, it is expected to normalize the diffuse cortical activation, reactivate the injured cortical area that has been inhibited, and favors its excitability. Furthermore, the high frequency rTMS (≥10 Hz) is expected to increase cortical excitability by reorganizing the cerebral connections, which leads to a greater efficiency of the neuronal networks of the affected cerebral area [10]. Corroborating with our findings, a study testing the efficacy and safety of low frequency rTMS in the treatment of resistant depression - although treating patients who did not suffer from stroke - also showed the remission of depressive symptoms after intervention with low frequency rTMS [11]. Another study also performed with post-stroke patients with high frequency rTMS (10 Hz) on (F3) compared the response of 20 patients - 10 subjects received active stimulation and 10 received sham stimulation. Their results also showed a significant difference in the HAM-D and BDI (Becker Depression Inventory) scores of patients who underwent the active stimulation, and the same difference could not be observed in patients who received sham stimulation [12]. We conclude that the findings of this clinical study suggest that rTMS may be able to relieve depressive symptoms and help in the improvement of the quality of life of patients with PSD. It is important that further randomized clinical trials be conducted with the same population, with the appropriate sample, blinding and control groups, in order to verify the efficiency of the intervention, as well as its effects in a follow up of more than one month. Conflict of interest disclosure:: There are no known conflicts of interest associated with this publication and there has been no significant financial support for this work that could have influenced its outcome. References: [1] Update S, Control D. Heart Disease and Stroke Statistics 2018. Am Hear Assoc 2018. https://www.ahajournals.org/doi/10.1161/CIR.0000000000000558 [2] Mackay J, Mensah GA. Global Burden of Stroke. WHO | Atlas Hear Dis Stroke 2018:50–1. doi:10.1016/B978-1-4160-5478-8.10019-3. [3] Duan X, Yao G, Liu Z, Cui R, Yang W. Mechanisms of Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation Treating on Post-stroke Depression. Front Hum Neurosci 2018;12:1–6. doi:10.3389/fnhum.2018.00215. [4] Kim JS. Post-stroke Mood and Emotional Disturbances: Pharmacological Therapy Based on Mechanisms. J Stroke 2016;18:244–55. doi:10.5853/jos.2016.01144. [5] Shen XY, Liu MY, Cheng Y, Jia C, Pan XY, Gou QY, et al. Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation for the treatment of post-stroke depression: A systematic review and meta-analysis of randomized controlled clinical trials. J Affect Disord 2017;211:65–74. doi:10.1016/j.jad.2016.12.058. [6] Bucur M, Papagno C. A systematic review of noninvasive brain stimulation for post-stroke depression. J Affect Disord 2018;238:69–78. doi:10.1016/j.jad.2018.05.026. [7] Chen J, Zhou C, Wu B, Wang Y, Li Q, Wei Y, et al. Left versus right repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation in treating major depression: A meta-analysis of randomised controlled trials. Psychiatry Res 2013;210:1260–4. doi:10.1016/j.psychres.2013.09.007. [8] Eche J, Mondino M, Haesebaert F, Saoud M, Poulet E, Brunelin J. Low-vs high-frequency repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation as an add-on treatment for refractory depression. Front Psychiatry 2012;3:1–4. doi:10.3389/fpsyt.2012.00013. [9] Benatti B, Cremaschi L, Oldani L, De Cagna F, Vismara M, Dell'Osso B. Past,present and future of transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) in the treatment of psychiatric disorders. Evidence-Based Psychiatr Care 2016;2:77–85. http://www.evidence-based-psychiatric-care.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/06_Transcranial-magnetic-stimulation.pdf [10] M. León Ruiza, M.L. Rodríguez Sarasab, L. Sanjuán Rodríguezc, J. Benito-Leónd, e, f, E. García-Albea Ristolg h y SAA. Evidencias actuales sobre la estimulación magnética transcraneal y su utilidad potencial en la neurorrehabilitación postictus: Ampliando horizontes en el tratamiento de la enfermedad cerebrovascular. Soc Española Neurol 2016:1–14. doi:10.1016/j.nrl.2016.03.008. [11] Brunelin J, Jalenques I, Trojak B, Attal J, Szekely D, Gay A, et al. The efficacy and safety of low frequency repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation for treatment-resistant depression: The results from a large multicenter french RCT. Brain Stimul 2014;7:855–63. doi:10.1016/j.brs.2014.07.040.
