N2  - In this symposium, I will first briefly present our recent systematic review on the cognitive effects of rTMS in depression, schizophrenia, and Alzheimer's disease, which reviewed the preceding randomized controlled trials to examine the effectiveness of rTMS administered to the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) and evaluated cognitive functions in these disorders. Second, I would like to talk about pathophysiology of the DLPFC focused on the neuroplasticity as indexed by paired associative stimulation (PAS) in patients with treatment-resistant depression using combined TMS-EEG technique. Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) is an effective clinical intervention for various neuropsychiatric diseases. However, it is still unclear how rTMS affects cognitive function. In this review, six previous studies demonstrated a significant improvement of executive function across these disorders. Moreover, no evidence for cognitive adverse effects was found in these included rTMS studies. Our review demonstrated that prefrontal rTMS could exert pro-cognitive effects on executive function and attention in some patients with depression but inconsistent cognitive impacts in any of the examined domains especially in patients with schizophrenia and Alzheimer's disease. Dysfunctional neuroplasticity is thought to be one of the pathophysiological mechanisms underlying depression. We assessed neuroplasticity from the DLPFC using PAS paradigm, which pairs a preceding peripheral nerve stimulation with subsequent TMS, in order to examine prefrontal neuroplasticity in patients with depression compared to healthy subjects. We analyzed PAS induced potentiation from the DLPFC calculating the power of TMS-evoked potentials. DLPFC-PAS induced a significant potentiation at the DLPFC in both groups. When compared PAS potentiation between the groups, patients showed a significantly lower PAS potentiation compared to healthy subjects. Our findings provide evidence for impaired neuroplasticity in DLPFC in patients with depression compared to healthy subjects. Such findings may ultimately help us understand the pathophysiology of depression and mechanisms involved in its treatment. Keywords: rTMS; TMS-EEG; cognition; psychiatric disorders; treatment-resistant depression
