N2  - Depression is the most common, treatable, mental disorder in late life, making it a major public health concern: 2 to 4 % of persons over the age of 65 suffer from major depression. Current pharmacological treatments for LLD, however, provide modest efficacy. Rates of treatment resistance in randomized controlled trials (RCT) in LLD range from 55-81% using first line antidepressants. The failure of first line treatment to induce remission in patients leads to impaired psychosocial function and diminished quality of life. Depression in older adults, and non-response to antidepressants, is associated with low connectivity in the cognitive control network. Cognition, in particular executive function and processing speed, are often impaired in LLD. It is an important predictor of acute antidepressant treatment outcome. In a 2010 report from the National Institutes of Health (NIH), depression was identified as one of six potentially modifiable risks for cognitive decline, AD, or both. Successful interventions targeting depression could reduce the prevalence of AD by up to 15% in North America, making depression the second most promising target for prevention studies after physical inactivity. Data from three randomized sham controlled trials that have included older adults show converging evidence for the efficacy of bilateral repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation in this population. Emerging data suggests that intermittent theta burst stimulation (TBS) is similar in effectiveness to high frequency rTMS. An ongoing study is exploring the effectiveness of bilateral (low frequency right then high frequency left) dorsolateral prefontal rTMS compared to continuous TBS right and intermittent TBS left in older adults with depression while also examining the effects on cognition. The design and interim results of this trial will be presented. Keywords: late life depression, transcranial magnetic stimulation, theta burst stimulation
