N2  - Introduction: HIV-associated neurocognitive deficit (HAND) has a prevalence of 30-50% in people living with HIV with commonly affected cognitive domains being learning, memory, and executive function.1 Pharmacological treatments such using combination antiretroviral therapy (cART) have nearly eliminated the most severe form of HAND, HIV- associated Dementia, however milder forms of cognitive impairment still occur.1,2,3 Despite viral load suppression, HAND does not improve with traditional therapy. Cardinal symptoms are bradykinesia and bradyphrenia as well as impaired prospective memory and difficulty in simple and choice reaction time tasks.1 We previously reported a preliminary study which suggested tDCS and cognitive training was superior to cognitive training alone in HIV-positive older adults.4 We did not previously report results of participants’ self-report of cognitive functions using the Patient's Assessment of Own Functioning (PAOF) scale. The purpose of this study was to evaluate the impact of cognitive training with or without tDCS on patient self report of difficulties in several cognitive domains. Methods: We used a free-to-play popular game called GT Racing 2 (Gameloft SE, Paris, France) requiring players to steer through simulated tracks of varying complexity. We enrolled nineteen participants 40 years of age and older with 16 completing the study (average age: 49.6; 12 men; 16 Black American and 3 whites) with HIV-related Mild Neurocognitive Disorder. Participants were randomly assigned to cognitive training with sham or active tDCS at 1.5mA x 20 minutes to the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex. They completed six 20-minute training sessions. We evaluated PAOF ratings in repeated measures analysis of covariance analyses as the interaction of time with treatment group, while controlling for demographic factors, immune status, and mood. Given the small sample size, we evaluated the impact of treatment using estimates of effect size (Cohen's d). Results: Our results suggest that cognitive training with tDCS has a statistically significant impact on self-report of difficulties in language (p =.04; d = 1.85), motor domains (p =.02; d = 2.24). Total PAOF ratings also differed between group (p =.04; d = 1.90) compared to cognitive training without tDCS. Treatment effects on the Memory and Cognitive/Intellectual subscales were non significant but associated with moderate to large effects (d = 0.81 and 1.31, respectively). We assessed the success of our blinding procedure by asking participants about their impression of what treatment group they were in. Most participants stated they believed they were in the active treatment group. The relation of participant belief to actual assignment was not statically significant. Discussion: These results are consistent with other studies showing tDCS may have a positive impact on cognitive training. Due to our small sample sizes, we analyzed effect sizes and assessing graphs of baseline and follow-up performance. Self-reports by participants showed improvement even after correcting for mood. Our observed changes in recall as well as PAOF showed larger effect sizes when depressive symptoms were accounted for compared to sham studies. Additionally, when mood was accounted for, our digit span backward and forward also had larger effect sizes. These results suggest that tDCS may have a useful role in improving cognition in HAND patients. This study is one of the first to investigate the potential usefulness of tDCS to enhance cognitive training effects in older adults with HIV. They support. Although we employed a single-blind design, participants were not able to identify their treatment assignment. Limitations of this study include our small sample size. Although results are suggestive, they await more definitive confirmation from a larger trial. A more extensive study allowing for a more thorough assessment of cognitive training and tDCS is currently under way. In this study assessments of additional factors related to participants’ function are included (R21 AG056256; NCT03440840). References: [1]: Woods, SP., Moore, DJ., Weber, W., Grant, I. “Cognitive Neuropsychology of HIV-Associated Neurocognitive Disorders”. Neuropsychol Rev (2009) 19:152–168 [2]: Wendelken, LA., Valcour, V. “Impact of HIV and aging on neuropsychological function”. J. Neurovirol. (2012) 18:256–263 [3]: Heaton, RK. et al. “The impact of HIV-associated neuropsychological impairment on everyday functioning”. Journal of the International Neuropsychological Society (2004), 10, 317–331. [4]: Ownby, RL., Acevedo, A. “A pilot study of cognitive training with and without transcranial direct current stimulation to improve cognition in older person with HIV-cognitive impairment”. Neuropsychiatric Disease and Treatment. 2016.
