N2  - Background: Abnormal connectivity of parietal areas with other brain regions is well-documented in Alzheimer's disease (AD) and schizophrenia. Furthermore, for treatment of depression using repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS), the parietal/intraparietal sulcus has been identified as a potential novel target. Rigorous, efficient techniques for precise targeting of parietal sites are needed to advance rTMS research. Here we describe techniques we developed for targeted rTMS of the lateral parietal cortex (LPC). Methods: In the context of designing a sham-controlled study testing bilateral rTMS to either LPC or DLPFC in mild cognitive impairment (MCI) patients, we had to solve three problems that were particularly evident for the LPC target: (1) MRI-neuronavigation, i.e. implementation of a connectivity-based targeting strategy to guide coil positioning; (2) Coil maneuverability, i.e. ability to steer the coil easily without impeded access to the right and left scalp; (3) Somatosensory stimulation to mask active-sham assignments. Results: (1) MRI-neuronavigation – The left and right LPC targets are MNI coordinates [±47, -68, +36], near the angular gyri. The left target was selected based on Wang's (2014) parietal rTMS study; importantly, these targets are likely to have good-to-optimal functional connectivity with limbic nodes affected by AD. We created concise operator manuals to supplement the Localite TMS-Navigator manual. (2) Coil maneuverability – Because of the bulky headrest and treatment chair, it was not possible to reach the LPC scalp sites. We built a slim headrest for LPC participants to enable greater access. (3) Somatosensory stimulation – Based on consultation and trial runs, we opted to place surface electrodes near the nape of the neck to deliver a low-amplitude current. This procedure, combined with an A/P coil that has realistic sham clicks, should provide successful masking in double-blinded research. Future efforts will be directed toward a clinically practical procedure for parietal targeting, analogous to BeamF3. Keywords: TMS, neurology, Alzheimer's, parietal
