N2  - Primary Progressive Aphasia (PPA) refers to the syndrome of progressive language loss resulting from neurodegenerative dementias. This study explores the effects of left hemisphere transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) on language production deficits observed in the non-fluent/agrammatic and logopenic variants of PPAs. Six subjects participated in a randomized, sham-controlled full-crossover study in which they received 10 sessions of tDCS. Participants performed a battery of clinical language tests prior to receiving either real or sham tDCS, immediately after 10 days of stimulation, 6 weeks, and 12 weeks after stimulation. In the Category Fluency task (a measure of verbal fluency) subjects who received real tDCS showed a significant benefit in performance over time compared to subjects who received sham stimulation. When change from baseline was compared between groups, participants who received real tDCS showed significantly greater improvement than those who received sham tDCS. There was no significant difference between groups on measures of picture naming, understanding of grammar, or semantic processing. TDCS shows a promising potential to ameliorate verbal fluency deficits experienced by PPA patients who suffer from impairment in this domain. 2 Introduction: Primary Progressive Aphasia refers to the collection of gradual and worsening language deficits that result from neurodegenerative dementias such as Alzheimer's Disease1,2,3. Non-fluent/agrammatic (naPPA) and logopenic variant PPA (lvPPA) are both characterized by prominent difficulties with language production; naPPA typically involves grammatical simplification, effortful speech, while lvPPA is associated with phonological errors and with poor word retrieval and repetition. Prior studies suggest that transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) could potentially play a role in ameliorating the language deficits that characterize PPAs4. The purpose of this study was to explore the effects of left hemisphere tDCS on several language measures that relate to the specific deficits observed in naPPA and lvPPA. We predicted that subjects with both naPPA and lvPPA would exhibit improvement in performance on tasks that rely on speech production—particularly verbal fluency—but that neither group would improve on a task that relies on semantic processing. 3 Methods: Six patients with a diagnosis of either naPPA or lvPPA were recruited from a large cohort of research participants at the Frontotemporal Degeneration Center at the University of Pennsylvania. All participants had been evaluated by a neurologist at the University of Pennsylvania and had received clinical diagnoses of PPA. Patients were excluded who were non-native English speakers, or who had a history of small vessel ischemic disease, seizures, other neurological conditions, unexplained loss of consciousness, or surgical breach of the skull. Patients who scored below 15 on the Mini-Mental State Exam (MMSE) were also excluded due to concern with global impairments precluding adequate comprehension and execution of task instructions. The study was approved by the Institutional Review Board at the University of Pennsylvania and all participants provided informed consent prior to participation. [Figure presented] Subjects participated in a randomized, sham-controlled full-crossover study. Participants received 10 sessions (one daily session, M-F for 2 weeks) of tDCS (1.5 mA; 20 minutes; 5 x 5 cm electrodes). The anode was placed over left prefrontal regions (F7) and the cathode over left occipital region (O1). During stimulation subjects narrated wordless children's books in order to engage the language system. [Figure presented] Participants performed a battery of clinical language tests at four time points: prior to receiving sham/real tDCS, immediately after 10 days of stimulation, 6 weeks, and 12 weeks after stimulation. Outcome measures: The tests employed in our language battery assessed many domains of language performance, some of which are more or less severely affected in patients with naPPA and lvPPA. The current analysis sought to compare domains in which both naPPA and lvPPA patients are typically impaired to those which are typically relatively spared. Therefore, the tests employed included a Category Fluency test (measuring verbal fluency), Test of Reception of Grammar (LTROG; measuring understanding of grammar), Pyramids and Palm Trees (PPT; measuring semantic processing), and Boston Naming Test (BNT). Separate two-way ANOVAs were used to analyze the effects GROUP (tDCS, sham) and TIME (pre-stim, post-stim, 6-weeks, 12-weeks) for each study measure. 4 Results and Discussion: In the Category Fluency task, subjects with both naPPA and lvPPA showed no main effects of GROUP or TIME (p > 0.05), but a significant GROUP x TIME interaction (p = 0.026; F=4.08; dF=3). These results suggest that subjects receiving tDCS showed a significant difference in verbal fluency performance over time compared to persons receiving sham stimulation. [Figure presented] However, post-hoc t-tests revealed no significant difference between subjects in the real and sham arms of the study at any individual points. Consequently, we evaluated the change in performance of both groups of subjects relative to their own baseline performance (Figure 3). A repeated measures ANOVA showed a significant GROUP effect (p = 0.021; F=11.16) indicating a significant difference between subjects receiving real tDCS and sham stimulation with respect to change from baseline. Subsequent post-hoc paired t-tests (Table 2) revealed significant differences between real and sham conditions at all post-stimulation time points relative to baseline. The divergence between real and sham stimulation with respect to change from baseline increased over the three follow-up time points, with the largest difference being 12 weeks following stimulation. This trend was largely driven by a decrement in performance in subjects in the sham stimulation arm of the study that was not observed in subjects receiving tDCS, suggesting that tDCS in this context may serve to delay the progression of language impairment caused by underlying neurodegeneration in PPA. [Figure presented] [Figure presented] There were no significant main effects or interactions for the other language measures LTROG, BNT, and PPT (all p's > 0.05). 5 Conclusion: The current results suggest that tDCS may ameliorate deficits of verbal fluency in PPA syndromes wherein verbal fluency is especially affected (lvPPA and naPPA). Intuitively, clinical language domains that are not traditionally affected in these PPA syndromes, such as semantic processing, are unaffected by stimulation. This may have implications for stratifying subjects and predicting treatment response in patients with PPA who undergo tDCS. It is important to note that our findings are limited by the small sample size. Nonetheless, our results suggest that future investigation may produce evidence that leads to better personalization of neuromodulation therapies for cognitive syndromes like PPA. References: 1. Gorno-Tempini, M. L., Hillis, A. E., Weintraub, S., Kertesz, A., Mendez, M., Cappa, S. F., et al. (2011). Classification of primary progressive aphasia and its variants. Neurology, 76(11): 1006–14. 2. Mesulam, M. M. (2001). Primary progressive aphasia. Annals of Neurology, 49(4): 425–32. 3. Grossman, M. (2010). Primary progressive aphasia: clinicopathological correlations. Nature Reviews. Neurology, 6(2): 88-97. 4. McConathey, E.M., White, N.C., Gervits, F., Sherry, A., Branch, C.H., Grossman, M., et al. Baseline Performance Predicts tDCS-Mediated Improvements in Language Symptoms in Primary Progressive Aphasia. Front Hum Neurosci. 2017;347(11)
