N2  - Inaccurate electrode placements in transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) may alter current distribution in the brain and affect stimulation outcomes. To date, there is no standardized method to monitor electrode location in tDCS clinical studies. Here we proposed methods to compute accuracy in landmark distance corresponding to tDCS electrode location using models generated from 3D scans. Landmark distances in the models were computed using curve and linear based methods and compared to their actual measurements in real objects. Our findings showed that landmarks in generated models were comparable to their actual locations, and that linear based method was sufficient to compute landmark distances in generated models. Methods presented in this study can be applied as quality control in tDCS studies involving an F3/F4 montage and expanded to include other electrode montages. 2 Introduction: Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is a non- invasive neuromodulation technique that can alter brain functions by applying a mild current (1-2mA) via two or more electrodes [1]. The electrode locations are typically determined using head measurements following the 10-20 EEG system [1]. Accurate electrode placements are important to ensure a sufficient current delivery to intended brain regions. For example, a previous study showed that 5% incremental drifts in electrode location significantly changed predicted current density distribution in the brain [2]. However, at present, there is no standardized method to monitor the accuracy of tDCS electrode location for quality control in tDCS clinical studies. In this study, we proposed methods to measure accuracy of tDCS electrode placements using 3D scans and distance calculation. Actual measurements of landmark distances indicative of electrode locations were compared to the same distances computed in generated models. Landmark distances in models were calculated using curve based (CB) and linear based (LB) methods. CB method requires manual labor while LB method can be automated for batch processing. Therefore, the aim of this study is to present a metric to compute accuracy in tDCS electrode location and compare the accuracy metric produced by CB and LB methods. 3Methods 3.1 Data Collection: A rectangular object with dimension of 18x25x29 cm and a sphere like object with diameter of ∼66 cm with fairly smooth surface were used as phantoms. In rectangular phantom, eight landmark locations were arbitrarily chosen on a flat surface of the box. Five landmarks were randomly chosen in spherical phantom to mimic distances of typical tDCS montage F3/F4. Landmarks in Dummy A (male) and Dummy B (female) were marked in Nasion, Fz, F3 and F4 location based on head measurements for F3/F4 montage following the standard 10-20 EEG system. The F3/F4 montage is currently used in a phase 3 tDCS clinical trial to remediate cognitive decline in healthy older adults. All landmarks in phantoms and dummy subjects were annotated using green stickers with a diameter of ∼6 mm. In dummy subjects, green stickers were placed on landmarks both before (PRE) and after (POST) electrode placements. Actual measurements of landmark distances in phantoms and dummy subjects were preformed using a tape measurement. Landmark distances of Nasion-Fz were computed as 30% of Nasion-Inion distance while Fz-F4 and Fz-F3 distances were computed as 20% of preauricular points through Cz following the 10-20 EEG system. Direct measurements defined as the shortest distance between landmarks of Nasion-Fz, Fz-F4 and Fz-F3 were also recorded during PRE and POST to determine electrode thickness effects on accuracy metrics. 3.2 Model Construction: After placing green stickers on landmarks, each object was scanned using 3DSizeMe software and an external 3D scanner [TechMed 3D, Quebec City] mounted on iPad air 2 [Apple Inc., CA]. Five consecutive scans were obtained for each phantom. In dummy subjects, five consecutive scans were performed before (PRE) and after electrode placements (POST). All scanned datasets were imported into MSoft [TechMed 3D, Quebec City] for preprocessing steps involving landmark annotation and model orientation. Cartesian coordinates associated with individual landmark locations were exported as a text file for LB calculation. 3.3 Data Analysis: The accuracy metric was defined as the discrepancy between landmark distances measured in actual and modeled objects, such that: [Figure presented] Where DistanceACTUAL is the actual measurement of landmark distance and DistanceMODEL is computed landmark distance in generated 3D models using CB or LB methods. CB method was completed on preprocessed models using a measurement tool within MSoft. Exported coordinates of landmark locations were sorted in MATLAB [MathWorks, MA] and verified in FreeCAD [www.freecadweb.org]. LB distance calculation following the Euclidean distance formula was then computed on sorted landmarks using MATLAB. 4 Results: Table 1A and 1B shows discrepancies computed in the rectangular and spherical phantom, respectively. Computed discrepancies between CB and LB methods in rectangular phantom produced similar values for all landmarks with an average percentage difference (PD) of -0.53%. In spherical phantom, PDs between CB and LB increased as the distance between landmarks was increased. Figure 1 shows discrepancies computed in Dummy A and Dummy B using CB and LB method. The average of actual distances measured in dummy subjects using direct measurements and the 10-20 EEG system were 102.17 mm, 69.42 mm and 69.33 mm for Nasion-Fz, Fz-F4 and Fz-F3, respectively. [Figure presented] 5 Discussion and Conclusion: Landmark distances computed on a flat surface (rectangular phantom) confirmed the landmark locations in generated models corresponded to their actual locations in real objects. Results in spherical phantom showed that LB method produced discrepancy less than 10 mm for typical landmark distances involved in F3/F4 montage. Plots in Figure 1A and B showed small effects (<2 mm) of electrode thickness on computed discrepancy. Figure 1C showed discrepancy of models and head measurements performed using the 10-20 EEG system, which served as a practical application of accuracy metric in tDCS studies involving F3/F4 montage. Computed discrepancy in all three distances for Dummy A was less than 5 mm and increased to 12 mm in Dummy B for Fz-F4 and Fz-F3 distance. The increase in discrepancy was probably caused by hair obstruction between landmarks observed in Dummy B that did not occur in Dummy A. Computed standard deviations in discrepancy using CB method were found larger than those computed using LB method. This finding implied that LB method produced more consistent results than CB. Further, LB method produced smaller discrepancies compared to CB in Dummy B. Therefore, LB method was shown sufficient to use for landmark distance calculation involving F3/F4 montage, especially with hair obstruction between the landmarks. This study presented methods to monitor tDCS electrode placements for quality control in tDCS clinical studies. Applications of these methods can include tDCS studies of a larger cohort using F3/F4 montage and can be expanded further to include different electrode montages. Future studies may explore other metrics such as consistency measure to track electrode location during multiple tDCS sessions. [Figure presented] References: [1] Woods AJ, Antal A, Bikson M, Boggio PS, Brunoni AR, Celnik P, et al. A technical guide to tDCS, and related non- invasive brain stimulation tools. Clin Neurophysiol 2016;127(2):1031-48. [2] Woods AJ, Bryant V, Sacchetti D, Gervits F, Hamilton R. Effects of Electrode Drift in Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation. Brain Stimul 2015;8(3):515-9.
