N2  - Background: Cognitive deficits are highly prevalent in patients with late life depression (LLD) and are known to persist in spite of successful antidepressant treatment. Preclinical and clinical studies suggest that transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) may enhance cognition however its effects in patients with LLD are not known. Methods: This randomized double blind sham controlled pilot study assessed the effects of a 2 week course of bilateral anodal active/sham tDCS of the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex on cognition in participants with LLD in remission. Working memory was assessed using N Back task and global cognition was assessed with a neuropsychological battery at baseline and at 14 and 90 days post intervention. Results: Thirty three participants were enrolled, out of which 18 (female = 13, mean (SD) age = 66. 3 (5.8) years) were randomized to active tDCS and 15 (female = 9, mean (SD) age = 66. 7 (5.8) years) to sham tDCS. All participants in the active group completed the tDCS course. One participant from the sham tDCS group dropped out during the intervention due to travel difficulties. There were no differences between the groups on working memory or other cognitive measures. On post hoc within group comparisons, active tDCS group showed improved performance on 1-back task at days 14 and 90 post intervention but the sham tDCS group showed improvement only on post day 14. Further, both groups showed improved performance within groups on working memory and neuropsychological measures. Conclusions: tDCS was well tolerated in patients with remitted LLD however it did not improve cognition beyond sham tDCS. Both groups showed practice effects. Improvement in attention was perhaps more sustained with tDCS. Future studies should explore longer duration of tDCS course and combine tDCS with cognitive exercises to exploit practice effects in patients with LLD. Keywords: tDCS, Late-life depression, Cognition
