N2  - Aims: Inhibitory control (IC) may allow cocaine dependents (CD) patients overcome craving and to maintain abstinence periods. Previous studies of prefrontal rTMS have reported reductions in craving in CD but data regarding follow-up with rTMS and cognitive effects are limited. This study sought to describe the effects on IC and craving after 3 months of rTMS treatment. Method: The study comprised a 10 weekdays double-blind placebo-controlled clinical trial (T0-T1) and a 12 weeks open-label rTMS follow-up (T2 1 session per week). Parameters: 100 trains at 5 Hz (10 s. inter-train) at 100% of MT over lDLPFC using eight-shaped coil. Cognitive data was acquired only at T0 and T2. Craving was measured with general and now Cocaine Craving Questionnaire (CCQ-G and (CCQ-G and CCQ-N respectively) and a Visual Analog Scale (VAS). IC was measured using a computerized Flanker Task and self-reported consumption (grams) was registered. Results: We include 11 patients in the study. After 3 months, self-reported consumption showed a significant reduction (T0: M=7.95, SD=11.66; T2: M=0.02, SD=0.09) (t10= 7.92, p=0.048). IC did not show significant changes after treatment, maintaining similar scores even with decreased consumption. We did find however, improvement in the reaction time to congruent signals (T0: M=476.80, SD=51.18; T2: M=447.84, SD=60.57) (t10=1.93, p=0.08) and to incongruent segments (T0: M=488.32, SD=51.41; T2: M=470.11, SD=68.68) (t10=1.18, p=0.26). Furthermore, CCQ-G total score showed a significant reduction (T0: M=199.64, SD=45.40; T2: M=109.82, SD=36.86), CCQ-N (T0: M=146.36, SD=37.13; T2: M=105.45, SD=31.40) (t10=3.48, p=0.006) and VAS (T0: M=3.564, SD=3.63; T2: M=.391, SD=1.01) (t10=3.05, p=0.012). Conclusions: After three months of rTMS treatment, craving and self-reported consumption decrease and confirm previous findings. Despite the decreased cocaine consumption, patients did not show an IC worsening as some previous studies have reported, which suggest that rTMS could prevent this cognitive decline while supports the craving attenuation. Keywords: rTMS, inhibition, craving, cocaine
