N2  - Introduction: Cognitive impairment following severe traumatic brain injury (TBI), especially in those victims with diffuse axonal injury (DAI), has been considered as the most debilitating neurological sequelae in this population. The potential benefits of repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS) for cognitive rehabilitation has never been tested rigorously in these patients. The primary goal of this study was to evaluate the immediate and delayed effects of rTMS over the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) on different cognitive domains of patients with DAI following severe TBI. Methods: Double-blind randomized controlled trial of patients with chronic DAI. Thirty-seven DAI patients were randomized to either sham or 10Hz rTMS to the left DLPFC. Neuropsychological evaluation included: Trail Making Test (TMT) parts A and B, Hopkins Verbal Learning Test (HVLT), Brief Visual Memory Test (BVMT), Five Point Test (5PT), Controlled Oral Word Association Test (COWAT), and Digit-Span. This evaluation was performed 1 week before (E1), 1 week after (E2), and 3 months (E3) following either sham or real rTMS.This trial was registered in clinicaltrials.gov (NCT#02167971) on 17 June 2014. Results: Thirty patients (17 real rTMS and 13 sham) with median age of 29 (22.5; 45.0) and 27 (23; 38), respectively, completed follow-up and were included in the analysis. Baseline data were comparable between groups. ANOVA for repetitive measures showed no significant differences between the two groups (inter-group analysis) in any of the tests performed. In respect to the primary endpoint, median TMT part B variation between evaluations E1 and E2 was -24 (-47.5; -4.0) seconds in sham group and -27 (-47.5; 22.5) seconds in real rTMS group (p=0.630). Minor adverse effects frequency during intervention was higher in real rtMS group (70.6% vs 46.2%, p>0.05) but this was not statistically significant. No major adverse effects were seen in both groups. Conclusion: High-frequency rTMS over left DLPFC was safe and well tolerated in chronic DAI patients. In respect to cognitive effects, no significant difference was observed between the two groups.
