N2  - Background: During the past decade, although repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) has been applied to improve cognitive function in patients with Alzheimer's disease (AD) or mild cognitive impairment (MCI), it remains unclear which combination of rTMS parameters stands out as the optimal rTMS protocol for A and MCI. The purpose of this meta-analysis is to determine the rTMS effects on cognitive function in patients with AD and MCI and to identify parameters of rTMS protocols that may moderate the rTMS effects. Methods: Databases searched included PubMed, EMBASE, and Web of Knowledge from inception to August 2018. Databases were searched using combinations of the following terms: [Alzheimer's disease, or mild cognitive impairment] and [repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation or rTMS or repetitive TMS]. Results: Twelve randomized, sham-controlled clinical trials with a total of 208 individuals with MCI or AD were included. Random effects analysis revealed a pooled SMD of 0.73, indicating an overall medium-to-large effect size favoring active rTMS over sham rTMS in the improvement of cognitive function (p < 0.0001). Subgroup analysis showed that the effect size estimated from MCI (SMD = 0.97; p < 0.0001) was greater than that estimated from AD (SMD = 0.64; p < 0.0001). In addition, the rTMS applied over the DLPFC or precuneus improved memory or general cognitive function; the rTMS over the right inferior frontal gyrus and superior temporal gyrus increased perceptual-motor speed. Conclusions: The pooled evidence suggests that rTMS improves cognitive performance in individuals with MCI and AD. Early rTMS intervention for individuals at high risk of developing AD is recommended. Future research that combines rTMS, neuroimaging techniques and comprehensive neuropsychological measures are needed to determine an optimal stimulation site and to better understand which cognitive domains and how brain activities are modulated by rTMS intervention. Keywords: meta-analysis, transcranial magnetic stimulation, Alzheimer's disease, mild cognitive impairment
