N2  - Introduction: The dorsomedial prefrontal cortex (dmPFC) and right temporoparietal junction (rTPJ) are key nodes in the theory of mind or ‘mentalizing’ network. Both have been implicated in autism spectrum disorder (ASD). We have previously demonstrated a therapeutic effect of dmPFC stimulation in autism, however recent functional neuroimaging suggests that rTPJ is a more viable target for social cognitive deficits in people with ASD. Methods: We are currently conducting a within-subjects, cross-over clinical trial comparing a four-week course of week daily intermittent theta burst stimulation (iTBS) to dmPFC and rTPJ in adolescents and young adults with autism spectrum disorder (n = 20). Participants undergo pre/post neuroimaging, clinical, and neuropsychological assessment for up to six months. Treatment sites are determined by T1 MRI-guided neuronavigation. Results: We present preliminary data comparing rTPJ and dmPFC stimulation using clinical, neuropsychological, and neuroimaging (fMRI) measures. Discussion: rTMS has shown therapeutic promise for both social, executive, and motor impairments in ASD, but there is a lack of agreement on the optimal stimulation site when targeting social communicative deficits. rTPJ is a promising region given its clear involvement in the neuropathophysiology of ASD, and the ease with which focal stimulation can be delivered to this region. The use of iTBS represents another significant advance for brain stimulation in autism, as it is more tolerable and can be delivered in significantly less time than conventional rTMS. Keywords: autism; theta burst stimulation; social cognition; clinical trial
