N2  - Background: Alzheimer's disease (AD) is associated with deficits in brain plasticity in the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLFPC) as assessed using transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) paradigm of paired associative stimulation (PAS). DLPFC plasticity has been shown to be associated with working memory (WM) performance. Mechanisms underlying WM are unclear however studies using electroencephalography (EEG) recorded during WM task have shown that theta-gamma coupling may underlie WM. Currently no intervention is known to enhance DLPFC plasticity, theta-gamma coupling or WM performance in patients with AD. Objective: To study the role of repetitive PAS (rPAS) of the DLPFC to enhance brain plasticity and WM performance in patients with AD, and to explore the role of brain plasticity and theta-gamma coupling as mechanisms underlying WM enhancement. Methods: 32 patients with AD (females = 16), mean (SD) age = 76.4 (6.3) years were randomized 1:1 to receive a 2-week (5 days /week) course of active rPAS (inter-stimulus interval = 20 millisecond) or sham rPAS (inter-stimulus interval =100 millisecond). DLPFC plasticity was assessed using single session PAS (via TMS-EEG) and WM was assessed using the N-back task before rPAS, immediately,7 and 14 days after the rPAS course. EEG during the N-back task was used at to assess theta-gamma coupling. Results: Only the active rPAS group experienced enhanced plasticity, theta-gamma coupling and WM performance immediately after the 2-week rPAS compared to baseline. However, these within group effects did not persist at 7 or 14 days following the 2-week course. Further, there were no significant differences between the active and sham rPAS groups. Conclusions: This small pilot study suggests that rPAS may have a positive impact on DLPFC plasticity, theta-gamma coupling and WM performance in AD but requires larger sample to confirm these findings and to detect difference between active and sham condition. Keywords: Alzheimer, rPAS, TMS, prefrontal, plasticity
