N2  - The study aimed to assess the feasibility and effect of transcranial Alternating Current Stimulation on Working Memory(WM) and processing speed in Schizophrenia (SCZ). Patients with SCZ (DSM-IV-TR; n = 11), on stable dose of antipsychotics were recruited for the study after screening for cognitive deficits using Letter Number Sequencing Test and Paper-pencil Digit Symbol Substitution Test. Age, sex and education matched healthy controls (HC; n = 15) were recruited for comparison of baseline cognitive profile. Resting EEG using 8 channels was acquired to calculate individual alpha peak frequency (IAF) in patients with SCZ. 10 sessions (2mA, 20min) of tACS at IAF adjusted theta frequency (theta=IAF-5) was applied over F3 and P3. WM was assessed using computerised numerical N-Back test and processing speed using computerised Digit Symbol Substitution Test (cDSST) conducted before 1st session (pre tACS) and after 10th session (post tACS). Side effects were measured using a structured questionnaire. On comparison of baseline scores in cognitive tasks – cDSST and N-Back, SCZ group had significantly poorer performance than HC group. SCZ group showed statistically significant improvement in accuracy of performance of both 1-back (t= -3.01, p≤0.01) and 2- back (t=-2.9, p ≤0.01) tasks after tACS. Improvement was also noted in reaction times of most of the parameters of cDSST. tACS was tolerated well with only minor side effects such as mild tingling, local pressure and sleepiness experienced during stimulation. Current study supports tolerability and safety profile of multiple session tACS in SCZ patient population. Our results show that application of tACS using theta frequency, as add-on treatment to standard pharmacotherapy, could result in improvement in WM and processing speed. This has the potential to improve functional outcomes in SCZ. Randomized parallel arm sham controlled studies and longitudinal follow up with concurrent examination of functional status would advance the literature on clinical utility of tACS. Keywords: tACS, Schizophrenia, Working Memory, Processing Speed
