N2  - Objectives: Cognitive impairment is highly variable in ASD, challenging treatment innovation efforts for this target. Within the context of a pilot clinical trial of repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) for executive function deficits in ASD, we performed functional neuroimaging using an N-back spatial working memory (SWM) task known to activate frontoparietal and deactivate default mode networks (DMNs). Methods: Neuroimaging was acquired in 40 participants aged 16–35 years with ASD (IQ > 70) with self-reported executive functioning impairment enrolled in the rTMS trial and 20 healthy control subjects. A visuospatial N-back task consisting of 0-back and 2-back conditions was performed during scanning. Measures of clinical symptoms and cognitive functioning were collected. Task-based fMRI analyses were performed using SPM12 (Statistical Parametric Mapping), and 2-back–0-back contrasts isolated brain areas active during increased SWM load. All reported fMRI results are multiple-comparison corrected using permutation analysis. Results: Performance on the N-back task was impaired in ASD versus control subjects (p < 0.05 across conditions); however, impairment was driven by a subset of participants with ASD based on 2-back performance. After a median split, a subgroup of 20 poor SWM performers with ASD was isolated. The poor-performing subgroup with ASD was significantly impaired compared with both control subjects and “more able” participants with ASD on measures of IQ, adaptive functioning, and executive functioning. As expected, N-back task performance activated frontoparietal and deactivated DMN regions across participants. Significantly less deactivation of DMN regions was found in poor-performing participants with ASD versus control subjects on the 2-back-0-back contrast. No differences between more able participants with ASD and control subjects were found. Conclusions: Using N-Back SWM task performance, we identified a subgroup of youth/emerging adults with ASD but without intellectual disability that featured greater cognitive and functional impairment compared with other participants with ASD, as well as altered DMN engagement during cognitive performance. Subtyping in heterogeneous disorders such as ASD may enhance identification of biologically homogeneous subgroups and enable the development of targeted treatments. ADOL, ASD, COG
