N2  - Sleep quality can be improved by enhancement of slow oscillation during NREM sleep using various scientifically proven techniques i.e. transcranial direct current stimulation and transcranial magnetic stimulation. Recently, rhythmic auditory stimulation (RAS) is getting popularity as a simple and straight-forward tool to enhance sleep rhythms and their functional efficacy. Therefore, we planned to improve the sleep quality by RAS in sleep disturbed university students. The students were screened for their sleep by Pittsburgh Sleep Quality Index (PSQI) and Insomnia Severity Index (ISI). Around 60% of university students participated in the present study showed significant and marked sleep problems. The sleep disturbed students were then randomly assigned to one of two study groups: active RAS and sham RAS. The participants in active RAS group were given the auditory stimulation in delta range for 30 minutes just before sleep each day for 4 weeks. No stimulation was given to sham RAS group throughout the study. The outcome measures were obtained at baseline and after the 4 weeks of the intervention. The sleep pattern of both groups was evaluated by Epworth's Sleepiness Scale (ESS). The Cambridge Brain Sciences (CBS) Battery was used to assess aspects of short-term memory, attention, reasoning, and planning. The P300 evoked potential was recorded during auditory oddball task as an electrophysiological correlate of cognitive performance. The results showed a significant improvement in sleep scores in active RAS group as compared to sham RAS group. There was a significant decrease in cognitive scores in all three tests i.e. Paired Associates, Odd One Out and Double Trouble with sleep disturbance. The 4 weeks of auditory intervention restores these cognitive performance deficits in active RAS group as compared to sham RAS group. There is associated delayed P300 latency with sleep related cognitive deficits. The auditory intervention for 4 week significantly improved the P300 latency pattern in sleep disturbed individuals as compared to sham RAS group. However, no change was observed on P300 amplitude in active RAS group after the intervention as compared to baseline. The present study indicates that 4 week of RAS ameliorates the sleep and cognitive disturbances in university students.
