N2  - Objective: This study aims to evaluate the efficacy and safety of laquinimod in patients with HD. Methods: The LEGATO-HD study originally included three dose arms, 0.5 mg, 1.0 mg, and 1.5 mg versus placebo, in a 12-month multicenter double-blind phase 2 study in patients with HD. Cardiovascular safety concerns were observed in multiple sclerosis studies with laquinimod doses of 1.2 and 1.5 mg. Although no similar concern was identified in LEGATO-HD, Teva discontinued the 1.5 mg arm in January 2016 as. Precautionary Safety Meas. and Continued to Evaluate the Efficacy and Safety of the 0.5 and 1.0 Mg Doses. Efficacy Assessments Include the Prim. Endpoint, Change from Baseline in Unified Huntington's Dis. Rating Scale Total Motor Score at Month 12, and the Secdry. Endpoint, Percent Change in Caudate Vol. at Month 12. Exploratory Endpoints Include Changes InMRI Vol. Measures and Changes in Q-Motor, CIBIC-Plus, UHDRS-Total Funct. Capacity and UHDRS-Funct. Assess. Scores. Safety Measures Include Adverse Event Reporting, Clin. Lab. Tests, Vital Signs, ECGs, Phys. Examinations, and Suicidality . Results: Three Hundred Fifty-two Patients Were Randomized. the Last Patient Visit Occurred in June 2018. Baseline Mean S.D. Pooled Demographics of Enrolled Patients Include Females N = 172 49.1%, Males N = 178 50.9%, Age 44.4 7.6 Years, UHDRS-TMS 24.3 13.1, UHDRS-TFC 11.1 1.7, and UHDRS-FA 22.7 2.4. Results of Prim., Secdry., and Exploratory Efficacy Endpoints, Along with Safety Findings, Will Be Presented at the Conf.. Conclusion: There Is A Significant Unmet Med. Need to Ameliorate Symptoms and the Progressive Neurodegeneration in HD. LEGATO-HD Provides Valuable Info. Toward Understanding the Efficacy and Safety of Laquinimod As A Potential Treatm. for Patients with HD.
