N2  - Introduction: Subjective cognitive decline (SCD) is a condition observed when a person reports worsening of their cognitive abilities, although examination fails to reveal objective evidence of this decline (Molinuevo et al., 2016). SCD is increasingly acknowledged as a risk factor for the development of Alzheimer's disease (Jessen et al., 2014) and has been particularly linked with deficient cognitive control (CC) functions (Stogmann et al., 2016). Anodal transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) to the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (dlPFC) can significantly enhance CC (Plewnia et al., 2015). Specifically, this has been demonstrated by means of a challenging and frustrating continuous performance task (Paced Auditory Serial (Figure Presented) Addition Task; PASAT) (Wiegand, 2016). This randomized, shamcontrolled study aims at providing evidence for the efficacy of a tDCS-enhanced CC training (PASAT) in participants with SCD. Methods: 30 subjects took part in a four weeks training. Half of them received 2 mA anodal tDCS for 20 min applied to the left dlPFC; the other half received sham stimulation. Eligibility criteria were examined by means of neuropsychological tests (CERAD-Plus, M.I.N.I.). Event-related potentials were measured with EEG as neurophysiological signatures of cognitive control. Near and far transfer were assessed by a Verbal 2-back Task and the Trail Making Test A & B. The amount of concerns regarding memory impairment is quantified by means of a 10-point Likert scale and serves as the primary outcome measure. Together with changes of PASAT performance these measures were obtained before and after the tDCS-enhanced training. Results: A one-way repeated measures ANOVA showed that, compared to sham stimulation, anodal tDCS during PASAT training significantly reduced the amount of concerns regarding memory impairment (F(1,28) = 6,48, p = .017, gp2 = .18) (Fig. 1). Performance in the PASAT task was improved by training but anodal tDCS did not enhance the performance growth compared to sham treatment (Fig. 2). These results provide a basis for potential interventional approaches in SCD.
