N2  - Objectives: Cognitive and mobility impairment are common in seniors and result in significant disability. Emerging evidence suggests that executive function is involved in gait regulation. HF-rTMS is a relatively safe non-invasive brain stimulation technique that has been shown to enhance motor learning and working memory. However, the role of HF-rTMS has not been adequately explored in prefrontal mediated gait function. We aim to explore the effect of bilateral prefrontal HF-rTMS on gait and cognition in seniors with executive dysfunction. Methods: Forty seniors with executive dysfunction (MoCA EIS = 8-11) will be recruited from clinic setting excluding those with dementia, severe depression or other neurological illnesses that directly impair gait. Baseline clinical, cognitive and gait assessments will be done and patients will be randomized to active vs. sham rTMS. Five consecutive daily active or sham sessions of HF-rTMS (20 Hz, 2000 pulses) to the right then left prefrontal areas will be applied. Patients and assessors will be blinded to the study assignment. Cognitive and gait measures are repeated immediately after the last session (day 5) and at 7 days post intervention. Results: Ten participants have completed the study so far. HF-rTMS was well tolerated with only one drop out due to head discomfort. Preliminary analysis shows significant improvement in memory encoding and a trend of improvement in semantic dual-task gait at 7 days post 5 sessions of HFrTMS in the active group. Conclusions: These preliminary results are encouraging.
