N2  - Background: Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) is a non-invasive and painless brain modulation technique that is increasingly used in research and clinical practice. The purpose of this meta-analysis is to determine the rTMS effects on cognitive function in patients with mild cognitive impairment (MCI). Methods: Databases searched included PubMed, EMBASE, and Web of Knowledge from inception to January, 2018. Databases were searched using combinations of the following terms: mild cognitive impairment and repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation or rTMS or repetitive TMS. Results: Six randomized, sham-controlled clinical trials (N = 107) were included in the meta-analysis. The total effect size of rTMS on cognitive performance was 0.86, indicating a large effect size favoring active rTMS over sham rTMS (z = 4.48; P <.0001). The main characteristics of the included studies are described in the Table. Conclusions: The random effect across the 6 clinical studies revealed a significant large effect size favoring active rTMS over sham rTMS in the enhancement of cognitive function in patients with MCI. However, as shown in the Table, stimulation targets/frequencies, treatment protocols, and outcome measures varied tremendously across the studies. Future research that combines rTMS, neuro-imaging techniques, and comprehensive neuropsychological measures are needed to determine an optimal stimulation site, and to better understand which cognitive domains and how brain activities are modulated by rTMS intervention. [Figure presented]
