N2  - Background: Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is a potential novel strategy for cognitive enhancement in patients with major or minor neurocognitive disorders, but stimulation protocols have not been optimized yet. Methods: A parallel, prospective, patients and raters blinded, randomized, sham-controlled trial was conducted. Patients in the active arm received tDCS (anodal; F3, cathodal; Fp2, 2A, 20 min) twice a day for 5 consecutive days. Calculation and reading tasks were conducted for 20 min during the stimulation. Primary outcome was attrition rate in the intervention group during the trial, which is expected to be less than 10%. Secondary outcomes were mean difference of improvement (positive means improvement) between groups in changes of mini mental state examination (MMSE), Alzheimer's disease assessment scale- cognitive (ADAS-Cog), frontal assessment battery (FAB), and clinical dementia rating (CDR) from baseline to day 5 and follow-up (two weeks after the final intervention). Results: 21 individuals agreed to participation in this trial and were screened at baseline. One participant withdraw consent to participation before randomization. After randomization, one participant in the sham group did it during the trial. Finally, 19 participants (7 in the active group and 12 in the sham group) finished the trial. No participants stopped the trial in the active group. No statistically significant difference was found in baseline characteristics between the groups. Mean difference of improvement between groups in changes of MMSE, ADAS-Cog and FAB at day 5 from baseline was 0.41 (p= 0.705), 1.61 (p= 0.205), -2.27 (p= 0.233) respectively. Mean difference of improvement between groupsin changes of MMSE, ADAS-Cog, FAB, and CDR at follow-up from baseline was 1.08 (p= 0.352), 0.36 (p= 0.791), -3.01 (p= 0.083), 0.06 (p= 0.404) respectively. Conclusions: tDCS is a safe and feasible technique in elderly patients with neurocognitive disorders. Future large-scale, well-designed randomized controlled trials will evaluate the effects of tDCS in those disorders more precisely.
