N2  - Background: JingzhaoToxin-V (JZTX-V) was isolated from the venom of spider Chilobrachys jingzhao and composed of 29 residues including six cysteines and three exposed tryptophan residues. Amyloid beta-protein (Aβ) plays an important role in memory loss and has been shown to suppress long-term potentiation (LTP). In the current study, we aimed to investigate the effects of JZTX-V on learning and memory behavior and suppressed LTP induced by Aβ. Methods: C57bl mice were treated with JZTXL (10, 100 nM, icv, n=14) and Donepezil (5 mg/kg, p.o, positive control, n=14) for 7 days, learning and memory impairment and LTP suppression was induced by Aβ1-42. Animal behavior was evaluated by Morris water maze and Step-through test, latency, swimming distance, type of searching strategy were used to evaluate spacial learning and memory ability and error frequency and latency were recorded to test passive avoidance response. Extracellular technique was used to determine effects of JZTX-V on LTP induction in medial perforant path dentate granule cell synapses, single- pulse stimulation was delivered to perforant path fibers in vivo, LTP was induced by 5-theta burst stimulation protocols (TBS). Results: JZTX-V restored the suppressed LTP induced by Aβ1-42 (50 nM) dose dependently. The amplitude of population spike of high dose and low dose JZTX-V were increased from 114±14 % to 184± 21 % and from 110±12 % to 207± 24% of control individually in perforant path-dentate gyrus pathway 30 minutes after TBS (P<0.001). From behavior testing results, JZTX-V significantly reduced latency，swimming distance, improved directness of path to the platform in place navigation test. JZTX-V significantly increased the latency into the dark chamber and decreased the error frequency in acquisition trial of step-through test (P < 0.05). Conclusions: JZTX-V significantly improved impaired learning and memory and restored suppressed LTP induced by beta-amyloid, which showed potential to be a promising new trial drug for Alzheimer's disease and dementia. The present study gave the strong evidence that learning and memory behavior is associated with LTP. This is the first report about JZTX-V on learning and memory and LTP. (NSFC 81373418.）
