N2  - Objective: To review the current evidence for cerebellar modulation in movement disorders and its safety profile. Background: The cerebellum has been linked to the pathophysiology of several movement disorders, such as cerebellar ataxia, dystonia, Parkinson's disease (PD) tremor, levodopa-induced dyskinesias (LID), essential tremor (ET), and progressive supranuclear palsy (PSP). Methods: We included published reports that clearly stated and measured clinical outcomes of movement disorders after neuromodulation interventions over the posterior fossa. The secondary outcome was the occurrence of adverse effects. We systematically searched Medline, Embase, Cochrane, and Google Scholar. The last search was run on May 27th, 2017. We searched for the terms PD, ataxia, dystonia, tremor, dyskinesias, and PSP in combination with terms describing the type of stimulation (transcranial magnetic stimulation [TMS], transcranial direct current stimulation [tDCS] and deep brain stimulation [DBS]) and the stimulation site (cerebellum, posterior cranium fossa, and cerebellar nuclei). Results: A total of 34 studies were included in this review [Figure 1]. The most robust effect was seen in patients with cerebellar ataxia, 1, 2 which was the most studied movement disorder regarding cerebellar modulation. Out of 13 studies, only one reported no improvement. No trial testing cerebellar modulation for hand dystonia reported positive outcomes. Out of 5 studies with cervical dystonia (CD) only one failed to show clinical improvement. ET had dubious results, since there was clinical improvement in half of studies. In trials with PD patients, the only clinical improvement reported was regarding LID. A single study reported improvement in dysarthria in PSP patients after cerebellar TMS [Table 1]. Only 3 studies reported side effects. Conclusions: Our findings suggest that cerebellar neuromodulation could be a promising therapeutic option to relieve some specific symptoms in certain movement disorders. Overall, the studies showed that cerebellar stimulation improved: i) cerebellar ataxia (of vascular and degenerative etiologies); ii) cervical dystonia; iii) tremor in ET; iv) LID in PD patients; v) gross upper limb movement in PD patients; and vi) dysarthria in PSP patients. Overall, all the neuromodulation techniques were safe and well tolerated, with only 3 out of 23 studies reporting side effects (11 of 34 studies did not mention if adverse events were observed). Of those adverse events, only one (DBS device infection) was considered potentially dangerous.
