N2  - Objective: To test the feasibility of a remotely supervised (telemonitored), at home tDCS paradigm paired with cognitive training for Parkinson's disease (PD) patients to improve fatigue and cognition. (Figure 1) Background: tDCS is a non-invasive brain stimulation technique that modulates neuronal activity in a painless and safe manner (Nitsche, 2008). We established a 'tele-monitored' protocol while maintaining clinical trial standards, and allowing patients to receive therapy in the comfort of their homes (Kasschau, 2016). Methods: It is a double-blind, randomized, sham-controlled study with remotely-monitored tDCS through a video-conferencing platform. We tested the feasibility and preliminary effects of RS-tDCS using a dorsolateral prefrontal cortex montage to ease fatigue and cognitive slowing in PD (Table 1). Participants were asked to complete 10 daily sessions with the option to choose 10 additional sessions. Feasibility outcomes and exploratory assessments were obtained at baseline and after 10 tDCS sessions of 20 minutes with 2 milliamperes (mA) intensity while participants engaged in computerized cognitive training. Acceptability of therapy, tolerability, side effects and other adverse events (AEs) were collected. Results: A total of 12 participants completed 230 rs-tDCS sessions; only 1 participant did not choose to complete the 10 optional sessions. Tolerability of 2mA stimulation with reported pain 56 in intensity on (Table presented) visual analog scale for pain (VAS-Pain) was 100%. Systematically recorded side effects were: tingling 20.0%, itching 6.5%, burning sensation 8.3%, dizziness 0.4%, headache 2.2%, sleepiness 0.4%, and nausea 0.4%. No serious AEs were reported. Compliance was 100% and subjects completed all required visits with no attrition or interruptions. Conclusions: The side effects and AEs of our RS-tDCS protocol were comparable to other previously published studies using conventional tDCS in lab settings. All our enrolled participants completed all scheduled daily encounters and performed the computerized cognitive training. Overall, we have determined that the use of at-home, telemonitored tDCS therapy is acceptable and well-tolerated by PD patients, with the advantages of ease of recruit and subject retention. Optimal acceptability was made by easy setup and intuitive design of the device. Our sample size limits our analysis of efficacy. The successful completion of our study will test this therapeutic approach on fatigue and cognitive slowing in PD.
