N2  - Introduction: Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is a promising noninvasive neuromodulation technique with therapeutic potential across many CNS disorders. It is often paired with rehabilitation strategies to improve training outcomes. Large scale clinical trials are needed to determine its benefits and guide therapeutic use. Following completion of two remotely supervised tDCS pilot studies, we suggest guidelines for future tDCS clinical trials completed away from the clinic as well as the feasibility of our protocol. Methods: Participants with multiple sclerosis (MS) were recruited and completed two at-home cognitive remediation studies paired with tDCS. Study 1 was conducted through Stony Brook University while study 2 was conducted through New York University Langone Medical Center. Study 1 was an openlabel pilot study in which all participants knowingly received 1.5 mA tDCS for 10 at-home sessions. Study 2 was a double-blinded controlled study that used 2.0 mA tDCS for 20 at-home sessions. The previously reported remotely supervised tDCS procedures were used in both pilot studies. Results: We report our trial experience with n=57 participants enrolled across both studies with nearly 1000 remote tDCS sessions conducted. Participants with MS (n= 26) were enrolled in study 1, of which only two participants were prematurely discontinued from treatment as per study protocol. For the double-blinded controlled study, n=31 participants were enrolled and five were discontinued from treatment as per study protocol. This study is ongoing and is currently recruiting for a study arm that targets 40 sessions with 2.5 mA of stimulation. Protocol compliance has been high with >85% completion rate to date. Additionally there have been no serious adverse effects and sessions have been well tolerated following reporting and assessment of stimulation side effects. Both side effect rates and sham integrity data will be presented from the controlled trial. Conclusion: The remote supervision guidelines described have proved effective in regards to our pilot trials. Following our experience with these trials, we have gained insight for future, larger-scale clinical trials. Simplified electrode placement and preparation proved a boon for our studies and enabled participation of multiple sclerosis patients with considerable cognitive and motor deficits. Additionally, a rigorous remote supervision protocol is necessary to facilitate repeatable and efficient stimulation sessions away from the clinic. A larger clinical trial that encompasses the lessons learned from these two trials will be conducted and reported in the near future.
