N2  - Background: Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation is a promising tool to study and modulate brain plasticity and connectivity. Objective: The aim of this study was to investigate the effects of theta burst stimulation (TBS) on dorsal attentional resting state network. Patients and Methods/Material and Methods: Twenty healthy young subjects participated in the TBS-fMRI study. Each participant received a session of stimulation of the right inferior frontal gyrus (IFG), the left superior parietal lobule (SPL), and the vertex (VTX) using continuous TBS (cTBS) or intermittent TBS (iTBS) protocol in a randomized order. Altogether 6 sessions of stimulation were completed by each subject. Prior to and right after each stimulation session each participant performed an fMRI Stroop task and resting state fMRI measurement in 3T Siemens Prisma. Results: Seed based analysis of resting state data of twenty young healthy subjects showed a significant increase in connectivity after intermittent theta burst stimulation of left SPL between SPL and the nodule of the cerebellum. This stimulation significantly increased connectivity within dorsal attentional network. Conclusion: Our results reveal that using TBS we might modify cognitive speed and intranetwork connectivity. We believe that this increase in connectivity after stimulation in dorsal attentional network might even induce behavioral effects in seniors or patients with mild cognitive impairment which are our future population targets.
