N2  - Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) has been shown to be a valuable adjunct to speech and language therapy, mainly in stroke rehabilitation and recently in primary progressive aphasia. An intriguing question that has not been addressed is whether different brain pathologies, atrophy patterns and symptoms associated with each variant of PPA have a differential impact on the effectiveness of electrical stimulation. We conducted a randomized sham-controlled, double-blind clinical trial using a within-subjects crossover design and we compared effects of tDCS coupled with oral and written naming therapy vs. sham coupled with oral and written naming therapy in three variants of PPA associated with different neurodegenerative diseases and with different brain atrophy patterns. A group of 27 patients with PPA (ten logopenic, nine non-fluent and eight semantic participants) underwent intensive written naming/ spelling therapy for 15 daily sessions of anodal electrical stimulation and 15 daily sessions of sham separated by two months, using an individuallytailored protocol of intervention. We measured percentages of correct graphemic units in trained and untrained words before, immediately after, two weeks and two months post-intervention. Written naming/spelling of trained words improved in all variants for trained words. For untrained words there was a significant advantage of tDCS over sham immediately after and up to two months in both the logopenic and non-fluent variants, but not in the semantic variant inwhich therapy gains did not generalize to untrained words. Our results provide the first evidence that the effects of tDCS on language outcomes may differ by PPA variant.
