N2  - Background: Deep brain stimulation (DBS) has proven successful in the treatment of Parkinson's disease and has received regulatory approval for increasingly list of applications. Among the relatively recent applications under investigation is to treat Alzheimer's Disease (AD). Policy and ethical consideration of the use of DBS should regard the context of specific disease or disorder that is targeted. Methods: Utilizing research ethics and norms as a starting point, this analysis explores the larger policy and ethical landscape for the use of DBS in the treatment of AD. Expanding the gaze beyond that of research ethics, this work identifies and analyses issues arising in results from recent studies, as well as standard considerations to examine and address the larger policy and ethical landscape for the use of DBS in the treatment of AD (DBS-AD). Results: The ethical issues in translational research include but are not limited to those within the purview of research ethics committees/ IRBs (e.g. informed consent and therapeutic misconception). Issues related to the details of and challenges in recent studies suggest a range of ethical issues in patient selection and trial design. Moreover, the larger policy landscape requires consideration of the context of this potential intervention in the treatment of AD, which can and should inform aspects of translational research in DBS-AD. Conclusions: A robust analysis of policy and ethical landscape of DBS-AD in both translation and possible clinical use, shows the need for careful attention to emerging ethical issues arising in recent clinical studies that may be overlooked by or fall outside of the scope of research ethics review. For successful translation and uptake of DBS-AD researchers will need to craft application in such a way that attends not only to ethical considerations but policy considerations, as well.
