N2  - Objective: To assess efficacy and safety/tolerability of four doses of pridopidine in HD patients demonstrating signs of motor dysfunction. Background: Previous HD trials, HART and MermaiHD, suggested pridopidine's potential to improve motor symptoms with favorable safety/tolerability. Pridopidine activity was originally highlighted for dopamine stabilization via low-affinity D2 receptor binding. Recent studies show pridopidine having highest affinity for sigma-1 receptors (S1R). In-vitro studies show pridopidine stabilizing medium spiny neurons and BDNF secretion in a S1R-dependent fashion, which suggests activity of pridopidine's potential beyond improving motor symptoms. Design/Methods: Patients were randomized to pridopidine 45mg BID (n=81), 67.5mg BID (n=82), 90mg BID (n=81), 112.5mg BID (n=82), or placebo BID (n=82) for 52 weeks. Primary efficacy endpoint was total motor score (TMS) change from baseline at 26 weeks. Exploratory endpoints included measures of total functional capacity (TFC), independence, quantitative-motor-assessment, behavior, and cognition. Results: TMS (primary endpoint) at Week 26 was not met for any dosage. Exploratory endpoints, with no correction for type I error for multiple comparisons, revealed positive findings. Reported P-values are nominal. TFC declined less at Week 52 with 45mg BID (n=75) than placebo (n=81) [LS mean difference: 0.87(95% CI: 0.29-1.45), P=0.003]. Compared with placebo (n=62), delay of TFC decline was particularly evident in the early-stage subpopulation taking pridopidine 45mg BID [n=59; Week 26: 0.56(0.04-1.08), P=0.036; Week 52: 1.16(0.54-1.78), P=0.0003] and 90mg BID [n=56; Week 26: 0.61(0.10-1.13), P=0.020; Week 52: 0.72(0.10-1.33), P=0.0239]. Additional endpoints supported TFC findings. Pride-HD did not reveal new safety/tolerability concerns. Conclusions: Pridopidine did not improve motor function at Week 26 compared with placebo. Pridopidine may confer delay in functional decline as measured by TFC, a measure of overall functional capacity. TFC declined less in patients treated with certain doses of pridopidine than placebo. A Phase III study confirming pridopidine's potential to slow functional decline in HD is warranted.
